                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.001 Larrea Alba, Luis/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-08-25T09:00:00-05:00"
                            >August 25, 1931—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. Referring to my telegram No. 37, Colonel Larrea Alba does not have title of
                    President but merely assumes chargé of the Executive power. See articles 79 and
                    81 of Ecuadoran Constitution. Larrea was thoroughly loyal to the last government
                    and took no subversive part in the movement against it. The transfer of the
                    Executive power to him has been effected in accordance with the constitution. In
                    the circumstances it appears to me that the question of recognition does not
                    arise and that the Legation should deal with the present government as the
                    lawfully constituted successor of that previously in power. I shall appreciate
                    an early expression of the Department’s views on this point.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
